Part I - Student Performance Data Exploration¶

By Benjamin Ogbonna¶

Last Updated August 23, 2022¶

Introduction¶

This is a dataset about students' scores/performance in a test.
The aim of this exploration/analysis is to identify if there are certain factors that contribute or affect students' success in a given test/exam.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

To understand the factors contributing to the success or failures of students

# Creating a another new column for grade, to grade students based on their scores (A, B, C, D or F):

# 0-59 =   F
# 60-69 =  D
# 70-79 =  C
# 80-89 =  B
# 90-100 = A

student_data['grade'] = ['F' if score < 60 else 'D' if 60<=score<70 else 'C' if 70<=score<80 else 'B' if 80<=score<90 else 'A' for score in ((student_data.total_score/300) *100)]

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 1000 tuples or rows of student performance, and 10 features:

  • 0 gender
  • 1 race/ethnicity
  • 2 parental level of education
  • 3 lunch
  • 4 test preparation course
  • 5 math score
  • 6 reading score
  • 7 writing score
  • 8 total_score (I added this. Not part of the main dataset)
  • 9 grade (A, B, C, D or F)

    • math score, reading score writing score and total_score are numeric, and the others categorical:
    Gender: male and female
    Race/ethnicity: A, B, C, D
    Parental level of education: high school, bachelor's degree, Masters, associate's degree, etc
    Lunch: free/reduced, standard
    Grade: was calculated by adding dividing total score by 300 and multiplying by 100

    What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

    I'd love to know/find out what factors contribute most to a students success or failure

    What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

    From a peek at at the data, I think features such as Gender, Parental level of education and test preparation course would play a huge role more than othersin my findings/analysis.

    In this section, I will investigate distributions of individual variables.¶

    What number of Females and Males took the test?¶

    In [88]:
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
values = student_data.gender.value_counts().values
colors = ["#0101DF", "#DF0101"]
plt.title('Gender: Female vs Males')
ax = sb.countplot(x='gender', data=student_data, palette=colors)
for x, y in enumerate(ax.patches):
    height = y.get_height()
    ax.text(y.get_x()+y.get_width()/2., height + .1, values[x])
plt.xlabel('Gender')
plt.ylabel('Fequency')
plt.show()

    From the plot, there were more females who took the test:

    Famales: 518
    Males: 842

    Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

    My variables of interest were categorical and numerical. And ther weren't any transformation to the data except for the two new columns created: total_score and grade.

    Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

    My data came in clean and hence no much cleaning was needed. For the two columns created, total_score was gotten by adding math score, reading score and writing score, and grade which was gotten by dividing total_score by 300 and multiplying by 100 and then assigning grades accordingly.

    What is the relationship between gender and grade?¶

    In [220]:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))

sb.countplot(x='grade', hue='gender', data=student_data)
plt.show()

    From our observation ealier, more females than males took the test. Now looking at the plot, it seems the females did better than the males in this test, because from the count, about 40 females got A while less than 20 males got A. Again over 160 males got F while about 122 females got F. this same trend is seen in the other grades as well.¶

    I think this could also be as a result of the fact that the ratioof females who took the test was more.¶

    Does math score affect or contribute to total score?¶

    In [280]:
    # Ploting to see any correlation between math score and their total score

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
plt.title('Correlation between math score and total score of students'.title())
sb.regplot(x='math score', y='total_score', data=student_data, color='g', x_jitter=.3, y_jitter=.3)
plt.show()

    There is a strong positive correlation between math score and total score.¶

    Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

    Based on features of interest (gender, parental level of education and test preparation course), there were many relationships observed during my analysis. For example, students whose parents are masters holders scored higher than the rest and students who completed the test preparation course got more A's. Also I found that more females took the test and did a little better than the males.

    Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

    I discovered a lot of relationship between other features like lunch and race/ethnicity as they also contributed or affected how well a student did in their test score/grade. For example those who had standard lunch did quite better than those with free/reduced lunch.

    Conclusions¶

    The aim of this analysis was to clearly understand how this features relate and how one affects the other. I also created two new columns total_score and grade so as to carry futher analysis as to which features contibutes or affects the grade of a students. It is seen that variables such as a parent level of education can affect a students score/grade in their test.
    Also another huge factor is the test preparation course, students who completed it seems to do better in their overall score/grade. Other factors such as lunch, race/ethnicity also contibutes as well.
